Abstract
The global public health landscape has been profoundly impacted by the
unprecedented COVID-19 pandemic, necessitating swift and effective strategies
to curb its spread. In response, predictive modeling of the novel coronaviruss
transmission dynamics has emerged as a crucial research area, providing actionable
insights for targeted interventions. This masters thesis delves into the realm of
COVID-19 transmission prediction using deep learning techniques, with a specific
focus on Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) neural networks.
To leverage LSTM-based deep learning models for accurate forecasting of COVID-
19 transmission. Predictive models based on LSTM are designed, and trained,
with a keen focus on optimizing their performance and generalizability. A
comprehensive evaluation, involving a range of performance metrics, unveils the
predictive accuracy and reliability of these models.
The findings and ensuing discussions shed light on both the strengths and
limitations of LSTM-based models in the realm of forecasting COVID-19
transmission. The thesis explores their potential applications to help guide public
health decisions within the country.
The implications of this research extend far and wide. Accurate COVID-
19 prediction models offer timely information to infor m resource allocation,
social distancing measures, and vaccination campaigns. By contributing to the
ever-evolving field of epidemiological modeling, this thesis aims to empower
policymakers and healthcare professionals with a valuable toolkit to combat
ongoing and future pandemics. Moreover, this work outlines avenues for future
research at the intersection of deep learning and public health, paving the way
for more sophisticated and adaptable predictive models in the face of emerging
infectious diseases.
Keywords: Deep learning, Long Short-Term Memory, Time series, Covid-19.

CHAPTER 1. INTRODUCTION
1.1 Background and Motivation
1.1.1 Background
Coronaviruses represent a continuous pandemic threat; humans have experienced
two coronavirus-related health security crises since 2003. In December 2019, a
previously unknown coronavirus was discovered in Wuhan city in China[1], [2],
then the WHO announced that the disease caused by the SARS-CoV-2 is referred to
as coronavirus disease-2019 (COVID-19). Caused by the novel coronavir us SARS-
CoV-2, has emerged as one of the most significant global health crises of our
time. Since its initial outbreak in late 2019, the virus has spread rapidly across
borders, challenging healthcare systems, economies, and societies worldwide. This
pandemic has highlighted the critical need for advanced tools and techniques to
understand, predict, and effectively respond to infectious disease outbreaks.
Figure 1.1: WHO statistics on the COVID-19 situation in the world.[3]
Epidemiologists and public health officials have traditionally relied on
mathematical models to forecast the transmission dynamics of infectious diseases.
These models, while valuable, often require simplifying assumptions that may
not fully capture the complexity of real-world scenarios. Additionally, the
unprecedented scale and speed of the COVID-19 pandemic have underscored the
limitations of traditional modeling approaches.
1.1.2 Movation
The motivation for this masters thesis arises from the desire to address these
limitations and leverage the potential of deep lear ning techniques, specifically
Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, in the context of COVID-19

prediction. LSTM networks, a type of recurrent neural network (RNN), excel at
captur ing sequential and temporal patterns in data[4], making them well-suited for
modeling dynamic disease spread.
This research endeavor centers on the enhancement of predictive accuracy in the
context of the rapidly evolving COVID-19 pandemic. Most of the existing studies
on the economic effects of epidemics are statistical mathematical predictions
based on disease spread models or literature-based predictions based on economic

1.2 Objectives
The overarching objectives of this research encompass the development of LSTM-
based predictive models tailored for COVID-19 spread prediction. These models
will capitalize on the temporal progression of the pandemic to capture intricate
data dependencies effectively.
The research will also delve into optimizing the architecture of LSTM models,
thoroughly exploring variations in model depth, the number of LSTM cells,
and other hyperparameters to achieve optimal predictive performance. To ensure

CHAPTER 2. LITERATURE REVIEW
2.1 COVID-19 Epidemiology
The COVID-19 pandemic, ignited by the emergence of the novel coronavirus
SARS-CoV-2, has posed unprecedented challenges to global public health systems.
The factors that caused the outbreak are still in the discussion phase. However,
many countries have been anticipating the transmission using social distancing
and activity restrictions except Sweden. Since then, not many predictions have
been available except qualitative and statistical analyses [7]. Understanding the
epidemiology of COVID-19, including its transmission dynamics, incubation
per iod, sever ity factors, and the impact of public health interventions, is paramount
to effective prevention, control, and mitigation efforts. This section delves into the
intr icate facets of COVID-19 epidemiology, providing a comprehensive backdrop
for the subsequent exploration of predictive modeling within this multifaceted
context.
The dynamics of COVID-19 transmission are multifaceted, posing a complex
challenge for modeling and combatting the disease. The virus primarily spreads
through respirator y droplets when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks,
but it can also be transmitted through contact with contaminated surfaces,
adding complexity to its transmission pathways. Although the basic reproduction
number(R0) has been estimated, real-world scenarios have demonstrated a wide
range of transmission rates. Super-spreader events have notably played a significant
role in disseminating the virus, highlighting the importance of comprehending the
factors contributing to such events.
The incubation period of COVID-19, which is the time between exposure
and symptom onset, varies from 2 to 14 days, making it challenging to
promptly identify and isolate infected individuals. Additionally, the virus
exhibits a wide spectrum of symptoms, ranging from mild respiratory issues
resembling the common cold to severe pneumonia and acute respiratory distress
syndrome(ARDS). Asymptomatic and presymptomatic transmission further
complicates case identification and containment efforts.
A pivotal epidemiological metric, the Case Fatality Rate(CFR), quantifies
the proportion of deaths among confirmed COVID-19 cases but has shown
considerable regional and demographic variation. The elderly and those with
underlying health conditions face significantly higher risks of severe outcomes,
emphasizing the importance of understanding factors influencing disease severity
6
CHAPTER 2. LITERATURE REVIEW
to allocate healthcare resources effectively.
Asymptomatic and presymptomatic transmission presents a unique challenge,
blurring the lines between infectious and non-infectious individuals. This has
necessitated widespread testing and contact tracing efforts to control the pandemic.
The emergence of new variants of concern due to viral mutations has raised
questions about increased transmissibility, potential impacts on vaccine efficacy,
and reinfection risks. Monitoring and comprehending the epidemiology of these
variants have become cr itical aspects of public health responses, requiring
continuous surveillance and research.
Herd immunity, achieved through vaccination and natural infection, has been
a subject of discussion, with ongoing research to determine the necessary
threshold and challenges in achieving it. Understanding herd immunity dynamics
guides vaccination and public health strategies. Despite progress in understanding
COVID-19 epidemiology, challenges persist, such as variations in testing and
reporting practices across regions leading to discrepancies in case counts. The
ongoing evolution of the virus and the emergence of new variants require
continuous research and adaptable public health strategies. Additionally, the
importance of data-driven decision-making remains paramount in the face of
evolving epidemiological dynamics.
In conclusion, the epidemiology of COVID-19 is a multifaceted and dynamic
field of study. It encompasses a wide range of topics, from the intricacies of
transmission dynamics to the factors influencing disease severity and the impact of
inter ventions. A thorough understanding of these epidemiological aspects serves as
the cornerstone for developing accurate predictive models. Such models have the
potential to assist in forecasting and managing the spread of COVID-19, ultimately
contr ibuting to efforts to combat this unprecedented pandemic.
2.2 Predictive Modeling in Epidemiology
Predictive modeling is a fundamental tool in the field of epidemiology,
empowering researchers and public health officials to forecast disease trends,
assess interventions, and allocate resources efficiently. This section delves into
the pivotal role of predictive modeling in epidemiology, highlighting its historical
significance, methodologies, and applications, with a focus on its relevance to the
study of COVID-19 transmission.
Predictive modeling has held a pivotal and enduring role in the field of
epidemiology, with a history spanning several decades. Notably, the inception
of modeling infectious diseases dates back to the early 20
t
h century, with
7
CHAPTER 2. LITERATURE REVIEW
seminal contributions from figures like Sir Ronald Ross, particularly in the
context of malaria transmission. These early endeavors laid the solid groundwork
for the evolution of modern epidemiological modeling, marking the genesis
of mathematical models devised to elucidate the intr icate dynamics governing
the spread of diseases. Within the realm of epidemiological modeling, a
diverse array of methodologies has emerged, each meticulously tailored to
accommodate the unique characteristics of various diseases and align with
specific research objectives. These methodologies encompass a spectrum of
approaches, including Compartmental Models, which include the Susceptible-
Infected-Recovered(SIR)[8] and Susceptible-Exposed-Infectious-Removed(SEIR)
models, intricately divide populations into distinct compartments, facilitating the
meticulous monitoring of disease progression. These models, characterized by
their capacity to unveil the complexities of infectious diseases and to estimate
pivotal parameters like the R0, prove invaluable in deciphering disease dynamics.
Agent-based models, an approach that simulates individual agents within a
population and meticulously replicates their interactions. This methodology shines
particularly bright when tasked with capturing the intricacies of heterogeneity and
spatial dimensions inherent to disease transmission, providing an intricate portrait
of how diseases propagate within a given populace. Time Series Analysis, a crucial
analytical tool, involves the systematic scrutiny of sequential data points over
time, serving as the linchpin for detecting underlying trends, seasonal patterns,
and recurring phenomena[9]. This analytical technique plays an instrumental
role in the ongoing surveillance of disease incidence as it unfolds temporally.
Machine Learning and Data-Driven Models, harness a spectrum of techniques
encompassing genetic[10], regression[11], Anomaly Detection[12], support vector
machine[13], and neural networks[14]. These techniques have ascended in
popular ity for epidemiological prediction, showcasing their prowess in navigating
the intricacies of complex, nonlinear relationships ingrained within datasets.
Deep Learning Models, exemplified by RNN and LSTM networks, are
progressively finding their place in the modeling of temporal dependencies
embedded within epidemiological data[15]. Their remarkable ability lies in their
adeptness at discerning and capturing the often intricate and nuanced patterns
concealed within time series data, rendering them formidable instruments in
the arsenal of epidemiologists and researchers alike. The extensive utilization
of predictive modeling in the field of infectious disease epidemiology has
encompassed a broad spectrum of diseases, spanning from influenza, HIV/AIDS,
and tuberculosis to the more recent emergence of COVID-19. These applications
8
CHAPTER 2. LITERATURE REVIEW
play a vital role in various aspects of disease research. Firstly, it plays a pivotal
role in disease forecasting, enabling the generation of forecasts about disease
incidence, prevalence, and the potential spread of diseases. These forecasts prove
instrumental for public health authorities as they navigate the intricate task of
resource allocation, the implementation of control measures, and preparedness
for potential surges in disease cases. Secondly, predictive models offer a robust
means for assessing the effectiveness of a myriad of interventions designed to
combat diseases. These interventions encompass a wide spectrum, ranging from
vaccination campaigns and social distancing measures to antiviral treatments. The
insights gleaned from these models are invaluable in the continuous optimization
of public health strategies, ensuring that interventions are tailored for maximum
impact. Furthermore, predictive modeling contributes significantly to the judicious
allocation of healthcare resources. This encompasses the allocation of critical
resources such as hospital beds, ventilators, and medical supplies. The modeling
process aids in the efficient distribution of these resources, with a particular
focus on regions that face an elevated risk of experiencing surges in disease
cases. Additionally, these models can be seamlessly integrated into epidemic early
warning systems. This integration enables the timely detection and swift response
to outbreaks by utilizing real-time data analysis and modeling techniques. Early
warning systems equipped with predictive models are capable of sounding the
alar m when new disease clusters emerge or when unusual patterns of disease
transmission are detected, thus facilitating a proactive approach to disease control.

2.3 Deep Learning and LSTM in Epidemiology
Deep learning, a subset of machine learning, has emerged as a transformative
technology in various fields, including epidemiology. In recent years, the
application of deep learning techniques, particularly LSTM networks, has gained
prominence in the study of disease dynamics and prediction. This section explores
the significance of deep learning, its evolution, and the role of LSTM networks
in epidemiological modeling, with a focus on their relevance to the prediction of
COVID-19 transmission.
Deep learning refers to the use of artificial neural networks with multiple layers
(deep architectures) to learn and represent complex patterns in data. While deep
learning has demonstrated remarkable success in computer vision, natural language
processing, and speech recognition, its application in epidemiology is a relatively
recent development. The advantages of deep learning models in epidemiology
include their ability to handle large and complex datasets, capture nonlinear
relationships, and adapt to temporal dynamics. The Evolution of Deep Learning
in Epidemiology has evolved over the past decade, driven by advancements in
computational resources, data availability, and model architectures.
The initial adoption of deep learning in the field of epidemiology centered on
10

specific applications, notably image analysis and bioinformatics. This early foray
into the realm of deep learning involved the utilization of convolutional neural
networks (CNNs) to tackle tasks such as the classification of medical images and
the analysis of genomics data, marking a pioneering stage in integrating advanced
artificial intelligence techniques into epidemiological research. Recognizing the
cr itical significance of temporal data in epidemiology, the field into the exploration
of RNN, including the well-regarded LSTM networks[4]. These RNN-based
models, renowned for their prowess in capturing temporal dependencies, found
their niche in epidemiology, proving exceptionally well-suited for handling
intr icate time-series data that characterize the progression of diseases over time.
The application of deep learning models extended further into epidemiological
prediction, encompassing a spectrum of tasks that encompass forecasting disease
outbreaks, estimating essential epidemiological parameters, and predicting the
spread of diseases. These applications took on newfound relevance and urgency
in the context of emerging infectious diseases, most notably highlighted by the
unprecedented challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic. A noteworthy trend
in the integration of deep learning models within epidemiology involves their
fusion with traditional epidemiological models as stochastic models, harnessing the
strengths of both approaches. This hybrid modeling approach offers the potential
to enhance prediction accuracy and encapsulate the multifaceted interactions
that underlie disease dynamics, marking a synergistic endeavor in the quest
for more comprehensive epidemiological insights. At the core of this deep
learning revolution in epidemiology lie LSTM networks, a specialized category
of RNN expressly designed for the modeling of sequences and time-series
data. Their ascendancy within epidemiology can be attributed to their unique
ability to confront challenges associated with temporal dependencies, a hallmark
of infectious disease transmission. Key attributes of LSTM encompass their
adeptness in sequence modeling, effectively discerning and retaining patter ns
embedded within data sequences, thereby rendering them a fitting choice for
captur ing the temporal evolution of diseases[15]. Furthermore, LSTM exhibits the
remarkable capacity to comprehend both short-term and long-term dependencies
in data, enabling it to adapt to shifting patterns and evolving trends over
extended time horizons. Their inherent flexibility in accommodating variable-

the intrinsic ability to autonomously extract pertinent features from raw data,
thereby diminishing the reliance on manual feature engineering, a process that

3.1 Recurrent Neural Networks
The persistence of human thought processes is a fundamental aspect of cognitive
function. When individuals engage in activities like reading, their comprehension
of each word is intricately tied to their understanding of preceding words. Rather
than commencing cognitive activities anew with each passing moment, human
thinking displays a remarkable degree of continuity. In contrast, traditional neural
networks cannot maintain such continuity, presenting a significant shortcoming.
For instance, envision a scenario where one seeks to classify the nature of
events unfolding throughout a movie. Here, the ability of a conventional neural
network to employ its reasoning about earlier events to inform subsequent events
remains ambiguous. The introduction of RNN serves as a notable solution to this
predicament. RNN feature internal loops that enable the persistence of information,
addressing the limitations of their traditional counterparts.

3.2 Long Short Term Memory networks
Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) techniques represent a pivotal advancement
in the field of artificial intelligence and deep learning, specifically tailored to
address the complex challenges of sequential data analysis. LSTM belongs to the
RNN family, but what sets them apart is their extraordinary ability to model and
comprehend intricate temporal dependencies and long-range relationships within
sequences of data. This makes LSTM a cornerstone of modern machine learning,
with broad applications spanning diverse domains.
LSTM was conceived as a solution to the limitations of traditional RNN,
which often struggled to capture meaningful patterns in sequential data over
extended time intervals. The crucial innovation of LSTM lies in its architectural
design, featuring memory cells and gating mechanisms that allow for selective
information retention. These components, such as the forget gate, input gate,
and output gate, empower LSTM to decide what information to remember,
what to forget, and when to apply this knowledge as they process sequential
inputs. Consequently, LSTM is exceptionally proficient in modeling sequences
with variable time lags and intricate dependencies, making them invaluable for
tasks involving time-series forecasting, natural language understanding, speech
recognition, and more. One of the remarkable attributes of LSTM is its versatility.
They can handle various types of sequential data, from financial time series and
climate data to text, audio, and even genomic sequences. Their adaptability has
led to breakthroughs in f ields as diverse as stock market prediction, language
translation, voice assistants, and healthcare analytics. The importance of LSTM
extends beyond its technical capabilities. They have significantly contributed to
the democratization of deep learning. Open-source libraries and frameworks have
made it accessible for researchers, data scientists, and engineers to harness the
power of LSTM for their applications. Consequently, LSTM has driven innovation
across industries, enabling advancements in autonomous vehicles, healthcare
diagnostics, recommendation systems, and more. As we delve deeper into the
digital age, where vast amounts of sequential data are generated daily, LSTM
techniques continue to evolve and hold promise for addressing complex challenges
in diverse domains. Their capacity to comprehend intricate temporal patterns and
make accurate predictions has reshaped how we interact with data and automated
systems. This introduction merely scratches the surface of the profound impact and
ongoing potential of LSTM techniques in the world of artificial intelligence and
machine learning.

Unrolling LSTM Neural Network Model over Time
In the architecture is depicted in the figure 3.11, the output gate is the final step
in an LSTM cell, and this is only one part of the complete process. Before the
LSTM network can produce the desired predictions, there are a few more things to
consider.
For example, if youre trying to predict COVID-19 for the next day based on
the previous 30 days of confirmed data, then the steps in the LSTM cell would
be repeated 30 times. This means that the LSTM model would have iteratively
produced 30 hidden states to predict COVID-19 for the next day.
The flow of information in LSTM occurs recurrently, forming a chain-like
structure. The flow of the latest cell output to the final state is further controlled
by the output gate. However, the output of the LSTM cell is still a hidden state,
and it is not directly related to the COVID-19 were trying to predict. To convert
the hidden state into the desired output, a linear layer is applied as the final step
27
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
Figure 3.11: Cells are chained together with the input sequence and output sequence.[23]
in the LSTM process. This linear layer step only happens once, at the very end,
and its not included in the diagrams of an LSTM cell because it is performed after
the repeated steps of the LSTM cell. Unrolling LSTM models over time refers to
the process of expanding an LSTM network over a sequence of time steps. In this
process, the LSTM network is essentially duplicated for each time step, and the
outputs from one time step are fed into the network as inputs for the next time
step. The unrolling process can be used to train LSTM neural networks on time
ser ies data, where the goal is to predict the next value in the sequence based on
previous values. By unrolling the LSTM network over a sequence of time steps, the
network can learn long-term dependencies and capture patterns in the time series
data. Backpropagation through time (BPTT) is the primary algorithm used for
training LSTM neural networks on time series data. BPTT involves unrolling the
network over a fixed number of time steps, propagating the error back through each
time step, and updating the weights of the network using gradient descent. This
process is repeated for multiple epochs until the network converges to a satisfactory
solution. One challenge with BPTT is that it can be computationally expensive,
especially for long time-ser ies data. This is because the gradient computations
involve backpropagating through all the time steps in the unrolled network. To
address this issue, truncated backpropagation can be used, which involves breaking
the time series into smaller segments and performing BPTT on each segment
separately. It reduces the algorithms computational complexity but can also lead
to the loss of some long-ter m dependencies.

Vanilla LSTM
A vanilla LSTM model refers to the standard and most basic form of an LSTM
neural network. The ter m "vanilla" is used to emphasize the simplicity of this
LSTM architecture when compared to more complex or specialized variants. In a
vanilla LSTM model, the core LSTM cell is used without additional modifications
or enhancements. Its important to note that while vanilla LSTM are the simplest
form of LSTM model, they are capable of capturing and modeling temporal
dependencies in sequential data, making them a powerful tool in machine learning
and deep learning. Researchers and practitioners often use more advanced LSTM
variants when specific features or optimizations are required for a particular task,
but vanilla LSTM remains a solid choice for many applications.

Stacked LSTM
A stacked LSTM model is a neural network architecture that involves stacking
multiple LSTM layers on top of each other. Each LSTM layer, or cell, processes
the input data sequentially and passes its output to the next layer in the stack.
This stacking of LSTM layers allows the network to capture more complex
patterns and relationships in sequential data, making it suitable for a wide range
of applications, including time series forecasting, natural language processing, and
speech recognition. Some characteristics of a stacked LSTM model:
Multiple LSTM Layers: A stacked LSTM model typically consists of two or
more LSTM layers arranged sequentially. Each layer processes the input data
and passes its output to the next layer in the stack.
Hierarchical Feature Extraction: Stacking LSTM layers enables
hierarchical feature extraction. The lower layers capture simple features or
short-term dependencies, while the higher layers capture more complex
patterns and long-term dependencies in the data.
Increased Model Capacity: Stacking LSTM layers increases the models
capacity to learn and represent intricate patterns in sequential data. This can
be particularly advantageous for tasks that require a high level of sequence
modeling.
Regularization: Stacked LSTM layers may require regularization techniques
to prevent overfittings, such as dropout or recurrent dropout. These techniques
help improve the models generalization performance.
Variable Hidden St ate Dimensions: Each LSTM layer can have a different
number of hidden units, allowing for flexibility in model design. Deeper layers
may have more hidden units to capture complex patterns.
Applications: Stacked LSTM models are used in a wide range of applications,
including time series forecasting, speech recognition, machine translation, and
more, where modeling complex sequential dependencies is crucial.
Its important to note that while stacked LSTM models can be highly effective for
certain tasks, they may also require careful hyperparameter tuning and training
to achieve optimal performance. The choice of the number of layers, the hidden
unit dimensions, and other architectural decisions should be based on the specific
requirements of the task at hand. In practice, stacked LSTM is often combined
with other neural network components, such as feedforward layers, attention
mechanisms, or convolutional layers, to create more advanced architectures for

solving complex sequence-based problems.

3.3.1 Smoothing methods
Smoothing of new COVID-19 case data is a crucial analytical technique that
ser ves multiple vital purposes in the context of understanding and responding to
the pandemic. The utilization of smoothed data is driven by several compelling
reasons that facilitate more accurate, insightful, and actionable interpretations
of the pandemics progression. Firstly, the daily reporting of COVID-19 cases
often exhibits significant fluctuations and noise. This noise can be attributed to
various factors, including variations in testing capacities, reporting delays, and
weekend reporting patterns. The irregularities in daily case data can obscure
the underlying trends, making it challenging to discern whether the pandemic is
experiencing sustained growth, decline, or remaining stable. Smoothing methods,
such as moving averages, are adept at filtering out these short-term fluctuations,
offering a clearer and more reliable representation of the overarching trend in
cases. Moreover, the smoothened data helps in the identification of patterns and
trends that might be otherwise obscured by daily volatility. Understanding these
patterns is vital for epidemiologists, policymakers, and public health officials.
It enables them to make informed decisions regarding interventions, resource
allocation, and the timing of public health measures. Smoother data provides a
stable foundation for predicting future trends and assessing the effectiveness of
inter ventions. Visualization is another critical aspect of the value of smoothed
data. Visual representations of data are pivotal in conveying information to
the public and policymakers. Smoothened data yields more visually appealing
and comprehensible charts and graphs. These visualizations are instrumental in
conveying the gravity of the situation and guiding public behavior. Furthermore,
smoothed data supports long-term analysis. When dealing with a prolonged
pandemic, it is essential to assess trends over extended periods. Smoothing helps in
discerning meaningful long-term patterns, which is invaluable for forecasting and
planning. In the context of decision-making, policymakers rely on smoothed data to
guide interventions and public health measures. Smoother trends provide a more
stable basis for making decisions about when and how to implement measures,
such as lockdowns or vaccination campaigns. Lastly, smoothed data is vital for
cross-regional or cross-country comparisons. It standardizes the data and makes
compar isons more meaningful. Policymakers and researchers can make informed
assessments of the relative severity of outbreaks and the effectiveness of different
strategies. So, the use of smoothed data in COVID-19 analysis is indispensable. It
reduces noise, reveals trends and patterns, aids in decision-making, supports long-

assessing disease incidence, particularly in the context of varying population sizes.
CPM is an epidemiological metric designed to measure and report the incidence
of a specific health condition or disease within a population while accounting for
the populations size. It offers a standardized way to compare disease rates across
different regions, countries, or populations, making it an invaluable resource for
public health officials, researchers, and policymakers. CPM is calculated using a
simple formula:

Standardization: CPM standardizes disease incidence rates, making it easier

incidence rates and accounting for population size, CPM methods contribute to
our collective efforts to safeguard public health.
3.4 Model Configuration
The architecture of the deep learning LSTM model used for predicting COVID-
19 plays a pivotal role in its ability to capture temporal dependencies and
make accurate forecasts. In this section, we delve into the intricacies of the
models architecture, including the network configuration, layers, and key design
considerations.
3.4.1 Network Configuration
The LSTM network employed in this research consists of multiple layers of LSTM
cells. The configuration of the LSTM network involves several crucial decisions.
35
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
The number of LSTM layers determines the depth of the network. Deeper networks
can capture more complex temporal patterns but may require more data for training
and may be prone to overfitting. Typically, one to three layers are used in LSTM
models for COVID-19 prediction, depending on the datasets size and complexity.
The number of units (also known as neurons or cells) in each LSTM layer affects
the networks capacity to capture information. A larger number of units can learn
more intricate patterns but may require more data and computational resources.
Careful selection of the number of units is essential to prevent overfitting and
ensure model generalization. Dropout layers can be incorporated between LSTM
layers to prevent overfitting.
In the LSTM modeling process, several key considerations come into play. Firstly,
theres the selection of input features, encompassing factors like daily case counts,
daily case smoothed and daily case per million. Secondly, the temporal sequence
length plays a pivotal role. LSTM models operate on input sequences of predefined
lengths. The determination of the appropriate sequence length is closely tied to the
specific prediction task at hand. For instance, predicting daily case counts might
necessitate sequences spanning the past few days, while captur ing long-term trends
could require longer input sequences covering extended time periods. Lastly, the
design of the output layer within the LSTM model is tailored to the precise nature
of the prediction task. In scenarios involving regression tasks, a solitar y output
neuron with linear activation is often employed to forecast numerical values, such
as daily case counts. These considerations collectively shape the architecture and
functionality of the LSTM model for effective predictive modeling.
Model training involves optimizing the LSTM networks parameters to minimize
the chosen loss function. In the realm of LSTM modeling, there are various factors
to consider for optimizing its perfor mance. Firstly, the selection of a suitable
loss function is contingent on the specific prediction task at hand. When dealing
with regression tasks, its common practice to employ the Mean Squared Error
(MSE) as the loss function, which quantifies the disparity between predicted and
actual values. Another pivotal aspect is the choice of an optimization algorithm,
which directly influences how the networks weights are adjusted during training.
Options like Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD), Adam, RMSprop, and others
are available. The careful selection of the optimizer, coupled with an appropriate
learning rate, plays a crucial role in ensuring the model converges effectively.
The batch size, dictating the number of sequences used in each training iteration,
is another consideration. It significantly impacts both memory requirements and
training speed. Many practitioners opt for mini-batch training, striking a balance
36
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
between computational efficiency and optimization quality when compared to the
more resource-intensive stochastic gradient descent. Lastly, to prevent the model
from overfitting the training data, the strategy of early stopping is employed.
This entails monitoring the models performance on a separate validation dataset
throughout training. When signs of plateauing or deterioration in performance
are detected, the training process is halted. This proactive measure ensures that
the model doesnt become overly specialized in the training data, enhancing its
generalizability to new, unseen data.
Evaluating the performance of LSTM models in predicting COVID-19 outcomes
is of paramount importance, and it necessitates the use of specific metrics tailored
to the unique characteristics of time-series data and epidemiological forecasting.
These metrics go beyond conventional evaluation measures to account for temporal
dynamics and the signif icance of accurate predictions in public health decision-
making. Common metr ics include Mean Absolute Error (MAE), which quantifies
the average magnitude of errors between predicted and actual values, providing
a straightforward assessment of predictive accuracy. Root Mean Square Error
(RMSE) extends MAE by penalizing larger errors more significantly, making it
sensitive to outliers. These are crucial for understanding the models performance
in forecasting COVID-19 cases, deaths, or other vital epidemiological factors.
Additionally, metrics like the Coefficient of Determination (R-squared) offer
insights into how well the LSTM model captures variance in the data, providing
a measure of goodness-of-fit.
3.4.2 Training
The training and validation process is a pivotal phase in developing a predictive
LSTM model for COVID-19. This section delves into the details of how the model
is trained, validated, and fine-tuned to ensure its accuracy and generalizability.
Model Training
The training of the LSTM model involves iteratively feeding sequences of data into
the network and updating its weights and biases to minimize a chosen loss function.
The key steps in model training include:
Forward Pass: During each iteration (or epoch), sequences of data from the
training set are fed into the LSTM network. The network computes predictions
for each sequence.
Loss Calculation: A loss function, appropriate to the prediction task (e.g.,
Mean Squared Error for regression or Cross-Entropy Loss for classification),
is used to quantify the difference between the models predictions and the
37
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
actual target values.
Backpropagation Through Time (BPTT): Gradients are computed by
propagating the error backward through time, considering the entire sequence.
This step addresses the vanishing gradient problem and allows the model to
update its weights.
Weight Updates: The gradients are used to update the LSTM models weights
and biases using an optimization algorithm (e.g., stochastic gra dient descent,
Adam, RMSprop). The learning rate and other hyperparameters influence the
size of these weight updates.
Epochs: Training continues for multiple epochs, where the entire training
dataset is processed multiple times. This repetition allows the model to learn
and refine its understanding of the data.
Hyperparameter Tuning
Hyperparameter tuning is an iterative process that involves systematically
var ying hyperparameters to identify the configuration that yields the best model
performance on the validation set.
Learning Rate: The learning rate controls the step size during weight
updates. Too high a learning rate may lead to overshooting the optimal
weights, while too low a learning rate may result in slow convergence.
Dropout Rate: Dropout is a regularization technique used to prevent
overf itting. The dropout rate determines the fraction of neurons to randomly
drop during training.
Batch Size: Batch size influences the number of sequences processed in each
iteration. It impacts both memory requirements and training speed.
Number of LSTM Layers and Units: The networks architecture, including
the number of LSTM layers and the number of units per layer, can significantly
affect model performance.
Early Stopping: Early stopping is employed to halt training when the models
performance on the validation set starts to degrade. It prevents over fitting and
ensures that the model generalizes well.
Learning Rate
The learning rate is one of the most fundamental hyperparameters in training
deep learning models, including LSTM. It determines the step size at which the
models weights are updated during gradient descent. A higher learning rate can
38
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
result in faster convergence but may overshoot the optimal weights, leading to
instability. Conversely, a smaller learning rate may lead to slow convergence or
getting stuck in local minima. Hyperparameter tuning involves experimenting with
different learning rates, often through methods like grid search or random search.
Learning rate scheduling techniques, such as reducing the learning rate over time
(e.g., learning rate decay), can also be applied to adaptively adjust the learning rate
dur ing training.
Dropout Rate
Dropout is a regularization technique used to prevent overfitting by randomly
setting a fraction of neurons to zero during each training iteration. The dropout
rate determines the fraction of neurons that are dropped out. Tuning this
hyperparameter involves finding the right balance between regularization and
model capacity. Hyperparameter tuning for dropout rate often starts with values in
the range of 0.2 to 0.5, and adjustments are made based on the models performance
on the validation set. The goal is to select a dropout rate that reduces overfitting
without significantly impacting the models ability to learn relevant patterns.
Batch Size
The batch size determines the number of sequences or samples processed in
each forward and backward pass dur ing training. Smaller batch sizes require less
memory but may result in noisy g radient updates, while larger batch sizes can
provide more stable updates but may require more memory. Hyperparameter tuning
for batch size considers a range of values, balancing memory constraints with
training efficiency. Its common to experiment with batch sizes such as 32, 64,
128, or 256. The optimal batch size depends on the dataset size, model complexity,
and available hardware resources.
Number of LSTM Layers and Units
The architecture of the LSTM model involves decisions regarding the number
of LSTM layers and the number of units (neurons) within each layer. These
hyperparameters significantly impact the models capacity to capture temporal
dependencies. Hyperparameter tuning for the number of LSTM layers often
explores configurations with one to three layers, as deeper networks can capture
more complex patterns. The number of units per layer is tuned to find the right
balance between model capacity and overfitting. Experimentation helps identify
the architecture that best suits the specific prediction task.
39
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
Patience for Early Stopping
Early stopping is a regularization technique that halts training when the
models performance on the validation set begins to deteriorate. The patience
hyperparameter determines the number of epochs with no improvement before
training is stopped. Tuning the patience hyperparameter requires observing the
models performance on the validation set over time. A smaller patience value may
lead to early stopping and prevent overfitting, while a larger value allows more
training epochs.
3.4.3 Evaluation
Walk-Forward Validation
In the development of a machine learning model, the utilization of cross-validation
ser ves the critical purpose of assessing the models alignment with the anticipated
trajectory. An effective cross-validation scheme is characterized by its ability to
faithfully mirror the distribution of the test data. This is of paramount significance,
especially in the context of feature engineering and hyperparameter optimization.
The rationale is straightforward: any modifications or refinements made during
these processes should ideally be indicative of the models performance on future,
unseen data. These modifications and optimizations are typically carried out with
reference to what we commonly refer to as the test set. It is crucial to be mindful of
the prevalent challenges associated with crafting an inadequate validation scheme.
In such cases, there is a notable r isk of inadvertently making adjustments and
enhancements based on validation metrics, only to later discover that the models
performance on unseen data is suboptimal. It is imperative to always bear in mind
that the ultimate objective is to cultivate a model that excels in the prediction of
future, yet-to-be-encountered test data
Many traditional cross-validation techniques are not ideally suited for the specific
demands of time-series data and associated problems. Common resampling
methods, such as bootstrapping (with the exception of time series bootstrapping)
and k-fold cross-validation, employ data shuffling procedures that do not guarantee
a cong ruent distribution in the validation folds compared to the actual test set. It is
important to note that the test data represents a future time period. To illustrate this,
consider that adopting these techniques leads to incongruities in the distr ibutions
between the validation and test datasets. This misalignment not only entails the
attempt to learn from future data while predicting past validation but also results
in the generation of validation scores that may lack accuracy. In the context
of platforms like Kaggle, a phenomenon known as a "leaderboard shakeup" is
40
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
Figure 3.16: Illustrates the concept of walk-forward validation.[25]
frequently encountered. This can be attributed to factors such as:
Overfitting to a small portion of the test set, which is reflected in leaderboard
scores.
Discrepancies between the test sets distribution and the validation data, lead
to suboptimal model selection.
While this is a nuanced topic that merits separate discussion, the key emphasis here
is to underscore the critical importance of employing proper validation techniques,
particularly in the domain of time-series data. Failure to do so may result in the
inability to discern reliable predictive models from suboptimal ones. In many real-
world time-series modeling scenarios, data volumes tend to grow over time. For
instance, our training dataset expands at regular intervals. Predictive tasks may
involve short-term forecasting (e.g., the next month) or projecting into a horizon
h, depending on whether classical time series models, machine learning, or neural
networks are employed. As each subsequent period elapses, more data becomes
available, necessitating the fitting or training of the model with this new data before
it can generate forecasts for horizon h once more. Given this dynamic nature, it
is sensible to adopt a cross-validation approach known as "walk-forward cross-
validation" or "expanding window cross-validation." This method aligns with the
evolving characteristics of time-series data and proves to be a practical choice for
assessing model performance in such scenarios.
In light of these considerations, it becomes apparent that the conventional train-
test split approach may exhibit superior performance when compared to k-fold
cross-validation methodologies. By organizing the data chronologically, from past
to present, and designating the latter portion as the validation dataset, this method
appears promising. Nevertheless, the train-test split alone may not offer an entirely
reliable gauge, as it carries the risk of potential overfitting to the specifics of the
41
CHAPTER 3. METHODOLOGY
chosen split point. In essence, the choice of where to partition the data assumes
significance in influencing the outcome of the validation process. To mitigate
the influence of chance and foster a more robust and dependable assessment, an
advanced technique known as "walk-forward validation" comes into play.
Essentially, walk-forward validation entails multiple data splits across distinct
per iods, with the training data progressively expanding in each fold. Professor Rob
Hyndman illustrates this concept very well with the diagram 3.16. This approach,
particularly relevant in applications like product demand forecasting, engenders a
more resilient evaluation of model per formance. Subsequently, the performance
metr ics are computed across the diverse folds, enabling the computation of an
aggregate metric, such as Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and weighted
MAPE (WMAPE), among others. It is worth noting that walk-for ward validation
need not be confined to a fixed one-period expansion. The flexibility of this
approach allows for tailoring the validation to closely align with the test data,
contingent on various factors, including data frequency, the choice of model (e.g.,
ARIMA, ETS, GBM), and the specific objectives of the analysis. This adaptability
allows the definition of varying initial lengths, data gain periods, and validation
hor izons by the particular context of the problem at hand.

4.1 Datasets
4.1.1 Datasets
The WHO coronavirus (COVID-19) datasets present official daily counts
of COVID-19 cases and deaths reported by countries areas. They serve as
the lifeblood of epidemiological research, underpinning predictive modeling,
informing public health strategies, and shedding light on the ever-evolving
dynamics of the pandemic. With transparency and accessibility at its core,
this repository democratizes the wealth of COVID-19 data, empowering a
global community of data scientists, researchers, and public health experts
to unravel the mysteries of this unprecedented global challenge and drive
data-informed responses. From 31 December 2019 to 21 March 2020, WHO
collected the numbers of confirmed COVID-19 cases and deaths through
official communications under the International Health Regulations (IHR, 2005),
complemented by monitoring the official ministr ies of health websites and social
media accounts. Since 22 March 2020, global data have been compiled through
WHO region-specific dashboards and aggregate count data reported to WHO
headquarters daily. Counts of new cases and deaths are calculated by subtracting
previous cumulative total counts from the current count. These counts are updated
incrementally throughout the day as more information becomes available. Daily
new case and death counts are completed by 23:59 CET/CEST each day. Due to
differences in reporting methods, cut-off times, retrospective data consolidation,
and reporting delays, the number of new cases may not always reflect daily totals
published by individual countries, territories, or areas. Details of this datasets are
descr ibed as follows:
Date_reported: Date of reporting to WHO.
Country_code: ISO Alpha-2 country code.
Country: Country, territory, area.
WHO_region: WHO regional offices: WHO Member States are grouped
into six WHO regions Regional Office for Africa (AFRO), Regional
Office for the Americas (AMRO), Regional Office for South-East Asia
(SEARO), Regional Office for Europe (EURO), Regional Office for the
Eastern Mediterranean (EMRO), and Regional Office for the Western Pacific
(WPRO).

New_cases: New confirmed cases. Calculated by subtracting previous

Cumulative_cases: Cumulative confirmed cases reported to WHO to date.

4.2 Implementation Detail
In machine learning and data analysis, a sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) problem
typically refers to a type of problem where the input data is organized as a sequence
of data points, and the goal is to make predictions or decisions based on the
order and relationships within the sequence. Seq2seq problems are common in
various domains and applications, including natural language processing, time
ser ies forecasting, speech recognition, and more. Time series forecasting is a
common type of seq2seq problem. Time series forecasting is a technique in
data analysis and predictive modeling used to make predictions about future data
points in a time-ordered sequence. Time series data consists of observations or
measurements taken at successive points in time, and forecasting involves using
historical data to predict future values. This type of forecasting is essential in
various domains, including finance, economics, weather, sales, and many others.
Seq2seq problems have 4 tasks such as one-to-one, one-to-many, many-to-one,
and many-to-many, with the COVID-19 dataset, only many-to-one and many-to-
many will be considered. Besides, univariate time series forecasting is a type
of time series analysis and prediction where the model uses only a single time-
48
CHAPTER 4. EXPERIMENTS AND RESULTS
dependent variable to make future predictions. In univariate time series forecasting,
the historical data consists of a series of observations collected at regular time
inter vals, and the goal is to predict future values of the same variable based
on the patterns and dependencies observed in the historical data. along with
univariate, Multivariate time series forecasting is a type of time series analysis and
prediction that involves using multiple time-dependent variables (multidimensional
data) to make forecasts of future values for one or more of those variables. In
contrast to univariate time series forecasting, which focuses on predicting future
values of a single variable, multivariate time series forecasting considers the
interdependencies between multiple variables over time. So, the Vanilla LSTM,
Stack LSTM, GRU, ConvLSTM-LSTM models will be applied to the following
cases:
Univariate time series forecasting with many-to-one task
Univariate time series forecasting with many-to-many task
Multivariate time series forecasting with many-to-one task
Multivariate time series forecasting with many-to-many task
In the univariate case, the models will respectively use the new cases and new cases
of smoothed variables that are created after applying the smoothed function, and
new cases and new cases of smoothed variables are used as target variables. Next
is Multivariate, the models will use two variables, new cases smoothed and new
cases per million, which are created after applying CPM methods to predict the
target variable new cases. Besides, many-to-one will have two cases, the first is to
take 7 days ago to predict the next day, and the second case is to take 14 days ago
to predict the next day. With similar many-to-many there are two cases, first takes
7 days ago to predict 7 days later, next takes 14 days ago to predict 7 days later.
More specifically with the ConvLSTM-LSTM model which is illustrated in figure
4.7, COVID-19 data is time series data, this belongs to the seq2seq problem, so
the ConvLSTM-LSTM model will use the ConvLSTM layer to encode, then the
following LSTM layers will be responsible for decoding. Finally, this model applies
the Dense layer to make predictions.

CHAPTER 5. CONCLUSIONS
5.1 Discusion
Covid-19 has been bringing the potential danger of diseases with a high rate of
spread while the capacity of medical facilities from the central to the local level is
overloaded. Detection of Covid-19 plays an indispensable role in the fight against
the impact of the pandemic. In this study, we made an attempt to develop a method
to predict the number of Covid-19 cases by applying epidemiological techniques
such as the smoothing method, the CPM method. From these techniques, we can
create variables with better data for the model and help the model predict more
accurately. When using the above variables to forecast the number of new cases
per day, a simple model, Vanilla LSTMs, can also produce accurate results, thereby
helping countries and health authorities to understand the epidemic situation so
that timely response measures can be taken. After Covid-19, one or more epidemics
may appear with a spreading speed and danger that may be even greater than Covid-
19. Therefore, early detection and diagnosis is always the top solution in preventing
incidents from unforeseen epidemics. LSTMs models have unquestionably proven
their worth in the realm of public health, playing a pivotal role in shaping policies,
fine-tuning vaccination strategies, and bolstering efforts to control the Covid-19
pandemic. Moreover, the prospect of deploying these models in real-time systems
is profoundly exciting. Timely decision-making and agile resource allocation,
dr iven by the insights gleaned from LSTMs-based predictions, hold the potential
to be a game-changer in our ongoing battle against Covid-19 outbreaks and future
health crises. The enduring legacy of this research extends beyond the current
pandemic. The knowledge amassed and the methodologies honed during these
endeavors will serve as a cornerstone for fortifying our defenses against future
pandemics and health emergencies. These lessons underscore the indispensable
role of data-driven, interpretable, and adaptive modeling approaches in the quest
to safeguard public health and protect communities worldwide.
Future Work
The LSTMs model has shown a significant development potential in the f ield of
time series data prediction. With many variations, LSTMs can handle data sources
with models of varying complexity. The power of the LSTMs model has been
proven in many studies and applied in many areas of life. So this model has
great potential for development and application in many newer fields. LSTMs
has also demonstrated its ability to handle complex problems. This capability
58
CHAPTER 5. CONCLUSIONS
can be expanded to address emerging challenges and problems, especially in the
areas of artificial intelligence and machine learning. With the Covid-19 pandemic,
additional variables can be used such as data on the number of people vaccinated,
the number of infected people, the number of recovered patients, etc. At the same
time, data on population movement is also very important in predicting disease
spread. Therefore, in the future it is necessary to apply more data to the model to
be able to discover the dependence of disease spread on the above variables.
